This is known as ‘jacking’. A clearance hole is a hole drilled in the top material to prevent jacking.

A hinge cup refers to a recession that is required for setting certain styles of invisible hinges. Hinge cup, cup hinge, Euro Hinge and invisible hinge are all terms that are commonly used interchangeably despite a few subtle differences. A hinge cup is one part of the invisible hinge that, along with the arm, makes up the movable half of a door mechanism. The complimentary piece to a hinge cup is called a mounting plate.
When setting the hinge cup, it is important to decide if the cabinet door is to have a profiled edge. If so then be sure that the router bit does not cut into the cups circumference. The hole drilled to set the hinge cup should be a flat-bottom hole drilled into the back of the cabinet door, and it is equally important to be certain that this drilling will not break through to the beveled edge of the door. The location and the depth of the hole will have some variance from brand to brand, but the diameter is generally 35mm.

A mounting plate is the part of a hinge, handle or latch that mounts the hardware to a cabinet. Mounting plates make it easier to attach doors to frames.
A mounting plate is the portion of a hinge that attaches to the wood. Mounting plates can be used in doors, cabinetry and furniture. They can also make it easier to assemble drawer slides. Mounting plates are available in a variety of sizes and finishes to ensure that each project has suitable hardware. The size of the mounting plate affects the door overlay, so carpenters must be careful to choose the correct hinges for their projects. Incorrect sizes may cause gaps or overlapping doors. There are also mounting plates on the market that are designed to be hidden from view, which can enhance the appearance of cabinetry. Some types of hidden hinges are installed inside the cabinet, while others are inlayed for a flush fit.

- Every VW tool is a plugin. Therefor, the objects that they produce are plugin objects. - A parametric object is an object without real physical values that can be defined by simply dragging your mouse cursor. A simple example would be a tool to create a rectangle, where the user can drag the width, but not the height. The height would be p.e. [width x 2]. The number 2 is a parameter in the Infopalet, and effectively the only way to change the rectangle's height. A complex example is our Window tool, where nothing can be drawn by hand. - The Plugin Object Styles made their entry in the US Window tool, which says a lot about their aim. In the meantime, even Title blocks have PIO Styles. A style is nothing more or less than a collection of parameters to quickly fill in the values. Our Window tool mimics that with the Favorites (this development was almost done when the PIO styles became available, so we missed that boat).

​Dutch lap siding takes the traditional lap to the next level. The angle of the bevel is sharper, creating more of a contrast between the planks. The troughs in the overlapped areas are deeper, creating an even stronger shadow line.
The goal with Dutch lap is to create a hand-carved look. This hand-made looking plank will create deeper shadows and smoother lines. Usually, these planks will be 4” or 5” wide.

​It is often called lap siding or horizontal siding.
Clapboard siding is designed with long, narrow boards of around 4”. These planks are nailed lengthwise to the wall of the house. They overlap each other top to bottom and look like wood in texture and profile. The overlap of planks produces a shadow line that creates an interesting profile. It is more subtle than other siding options that also overlap.
Each plank of siding has a rounded notch cut into the bottom edge. With beaded seam siding, you have an interesting shadow line.

Also called barn siding, board and batten siding is the widest of all, with planks of up to 12 inches wide. The boards are installed either vertically or horizontally, with narrow strips of wood nailed over the gap between the boards.

​Similar to clapboard siding, traditional lap is made of broad planks of 6” to 7”. These, also, overlap. Each plank is wedge-shaped, being narrower at the top than the bottom.
The planks are installed starting at the bottom of the wall, and the thicker bottom edge will overlap the bottom plank. This sheds water very efficiently, protecting the structure beneath. This pattern creates stronger shadow lines than regular clapboard.
Sometimes called “fish scale” siding, these are half-round shingles that create a picturesque look.

Wall closure suggereert het 'sluiten' van de muur.
Afbeelding 1 - Bij muren zonder luchtspouw heb je geen afsluiting. Er is namelijk niets om 'af te sluiten'. Er is alleen maar de aansluiting van de muur op het raamframe (of omgekeerd). Wat 'wall closure' hier doet, is de isolatielaag een beetje inkorten, zodat er plaats is voor een 'isolatielat' (die deel is van de raamassemblage).
Afbeelding 2 - Het 'sluiten' van de muur heb je alleen bij spouwmuren: daar wordt de luchtspouw afgesloten. Maar die afsluiting is het gevolg van de aansluiting tussen raamframe en muur. Wat 'wall closure' hier doet, is het buitenspouwblad verlengen zodat het raamframe tegen dat buitenspouwblad gedrukt kan worden.

Environment lighting and ambient lighting are two options in the Edit Renderworks Style dialog. Environment Lighting comes from the background that you use and Ambient lighting is global lighting.
In Vectorworks, "environment lighting" has a really specific meaning. It refers to when there's a panoramic image background that contributes to the lighting of a rendering. The background can just be a background, or contribute to the lighting or both.

Tracker drift is the steady increase in tracker error with time.
A tracker measures the position of a stationary object. As time passes, the tracker inaccuracy grows, which makes its data useless.
